**Full Text (summary, not verbatim)**:
Kyle Poyar argues that account-based GTM (ABM/ABX-style motions) is becoming increasingly important as AI reduces the cost of generating outbound messages. The result is a saturated environment where generic outreach no longer differentiates, making precision and relevance the primary competitive edge. He emphasizes that modern ABM is no longer just about targeting accounts, but about building a full system that connects data, workflows, and AI tools to orchestrate highly contextual engagement across a small set of high-value accounts. This includes combining enrichment data, intent signals, CRM workflows, and AI-driven research to identify opportunities and coordinate outreach. However, he also acknowledges the complexity: building such systems is operationally heavy and requires careful orchestration of tools and processes. The underlying message is that GTM is shifting from “broad acquisition” to “deep account engagement systems” where success depends on structured intelligence rather than raw outbound volume.

